\section{Strauss Section 1.3} 

\subsection{Exercise 4. Suppose that some particles which are suspended in a liquid medium would be pulled down at the constant velocity $V > 0$ by gravity in the absence of diffusion.  Taking account of the diffusion find the equation for the concentration of particles.  Assume homogeneity in the horizontal directions $x$ and $y$. Let the $z$ axis point upwards.}
   
\begin{solution} 
It is quite sensible to consider diffusion with gravity.  Applications could include a precipitant in solution for a biochemistry experiment or a passive heated source at the top of a (soon to be cold) classroom. \\

Letting $u(z,t)$ be the concentration at time $t$, then the mass is given by
\begin{align*}
    &M\left(t\right)=\int_{z_0}^{z_1}udz\\
    &\frac{dM}{dt} = \int_{z_0}^{z_1} u_tdz
\end{align*}
Fick's Law of Diffusion tells us that the movement from higher concentration to lower concentration is 
\begin{align*}
    \frac{dM}{dt} &= \int_{z_0}^{z_1}u_tdz \\
    &= \text{ flow in - flow out } \\
    &= ku_z\left(z_1,t\right)-ku_z\left(z_0,t\right) \text{, where $k$ is an arbitrary constant} \\
\end{align*}
\end{solution}

